    <!-- ======= Climate Change Section ======= -->
    <section id="climate-change" class="climate">
      <div class="container aos-init" data-aos="fade-up">

        <div class="section-title">
          <h2>Climate Change</h2>
          <p>Explore our VietNam</p>
        </div>

        <div class="row aos-init" data-aos="fade-up" data-aos-delay="100">
          <div class="col-lg-3">
            <ul class="nav nav-tabs flex-column" role="tablist">
              <li class="nav-item" role="presentation">
                <a class="nav-link active show" data-bs-toggle="tab" href="#tab-1" aria-selected="true" role="tab">Define</a>
              </li>
              <li class="nav-item" role="presentation">
                <a class="nav-link" data-bs-toggle="tab" href="#tab-2" aria-selected="false" tabindex="-1" role="tab">Reasons</a>
              </li>
              <li class="nav-item" role="presentation">
                <a class="nav-link" data-bs-toggle="tab" href="#tab-3" aria-selected="false" tabindex="-1" role="tab">Consequences</a>
              </li>
              <li class="nav-item" role="presentation">
                <a class="nav-link" data-bs-toggle="tab" href="#tab-4" aria-selected="false" tabindex="-1" role="tab">Physical Science</a>
              </li>
              <li class="nav-item" role="presentation">
                <a class="nav-link" data-bs-toggle="tab" href="#tab-5" aria-selected="false" tabindex="-1" role="tab">COP27</a>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="col-lg-9 mt-4 mt-lg-0">
            <div class="tab-content">
              <div class="tab-pane active show" id="tab-1" role="tabpanel">
                <div class="row">
                  <div class="col-lg-8 details order-2 order-lg-1">
                    <h3>What's Climate Change?</h3>
                    <p class="fst-italic">Climate change is a process which causes long-term changes in temperature and weather
                      patterns. It is putting not just ours, but also the animals' and plants' lives at danger by
                      trapping the heat from the sun and increasing its temperature.
                      Greenhouse gas emissions like Carbon dioxide and methane are the main
                      culprits of climate change, which can be found in a lot of human activities. Ever since
                      the industrial revolution, the temperature has been rising more quickly than ever before.
                      According to an UN report in 2018, Earth is now 1.1°C higher than it was back in the
                      late 1800s and would rise to 2.7°C by the end of the century.</p>
                      <p>- Nguyen Tra My _Sandbox JTC</p>
                  </div>
                  <div class="col-lg-4 text-center order-1 order-lg-2">
                    <img src="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/GiangSandbox/climatechange/main/img/earth.png?raw=true" alt="" class="img-fluid">
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="tab-pane" id="tab-2" role="tabpanel">
                <div class="row">
                  <div class="col-lg-8 details order-2 order-lg-1">
                    <h3>Why did it Happens?</h3>
                    <p class="fst-italic">Originally, climate change was only a natural thing, which could only cause small
                      changes in warming. But ever since the industrial revolution, humans have put their
                      hands into climate change, causing it to make more drastic changes. The main reason
                      of climate change process consists of:
                      <ul>
                      <li> Transportation (produces massive amounts of COz from burned petroleum-based
                      fuel)</li>
                      <li> Deforestation (Releasing CO2 stored in vegetation and soil annually)</li>
                      <li> Oil & Gas Development (leaks methane out from the operations)</li>
                      <li> Commodity Production (produces things like cement, iron, steel, electricity,</li>
                      plastic, and clothing are made by burning fossil fuels to create energy, which
                      create emissions)
                      <li> Excessive consumption (Our activities contribute to greenhouse gas emissions,
                      like how you use electricity, how you eat, throw away, what you wear, etc.)</li>
                      </ul>
                    </p>
                    <p>- Nguyen Tra My _Sandbox JTC</p>
                  </div>
                  <div class="col-lg-4 text-center order-1 order-lg-2">
                    <img src="https://www.vietnamonline.com/media/uploads/froala_editor/images/Saigon%20Traffic%20Jam.jpg" height="500" alt="" class="img-fluid">
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="tab-pane" id="tab-3" role="tabpanel">
                <div class="row">
                  <div class="col-lg-12 details order-2 order-lg-1">
                    <h3>Consequences</h3>
                    <p class="fst-italic">All causes have consequences, and the consequences to climate change have
                      brought us multiple threats.</p>
                    <p>The temperature will rise from greenhouse gases. With high temperatures, it
                      can increase heat-related illnesses, difficulty of outdoor activities, and a higher chance
                      of quick-spread wildfires.
                      Global warming heat is mostly absorbed by the ocean. This causes coastal
                      and island communities to melt ice sheets, raise sea levels, and increase ocean acidity,
                      endangering marine life. This has been affecting islands or seaside places like Venice,
                      Italy, which has been at risk of sinking.
                      Heat also evaporates water, causing prolonged droughts. Sand and dust
                      storms, desert expansion, and food scarcity are caused, threatening people's daily
                      water needs and their crops.
                      Other than causing droughts, heat can also cause more intense storms.
                      Leads to severe storms, flooding, and landslides, destroying buildings, houses, and
                      communities, which brings both loss of life and economic loss.
                      Factors that leave people in poverty increase. All the natural disasters have
                      an effect on them, like how flooding sweeps away homes and livelihoods, droughts and
                      water scarcity affect crops, heat causes difficulty in outdoor activities, and more. These
                      disasters displace 23.1 million people in the last decades, leaving many more
                      vulnerable to poverty.</p>
                      <p>- Nguyen Tra My _Sandbox JTC</p>
                  </div>
                
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="tab-pane" id="tab-4" role="tabpanel">
                <div class="row">
                  <div class="col-lg-12 details order-2 order-lg-1">
                    <h3>The physical Science</h3>
                    <p class="fst-italic">
                      <ul>
                      <li> Human activities have warmed the atmosphere, oceans, and land, causing rapid
                      and widespread changes to the atmosphere, oceans, cryosphere and biosphere.</li>
                      <li> The scale of recent changes in the climate system has been unprecedented for
                      centuries, even thousands of years. Many changes are irreversible over
                      centuries or even millennia, especially in oceans, ice caps and global sea levels.</li>
                      <li> Man-made climate change affects all regions. There is growing evidence of a link
                      with extreme heat waves, heavy rainfall, droughts, and tropical storms.</li>
                      <li> Global surface temperatures will continue to rise until at least mid-centurv. Unless
                      we make deep cuts in greenhouse gas emissions in the coming decades, if
                      global warming exceeds 1.5 degrees Celsius, then the climate consequences will
                      be even more severe.</li>
                      <li> The hotter the world, the more changes the climate system will have. This
                      includes more frequent and extreme temperature events, heat waves at sea,
                      heavy rainfall, agricultural and ecological droughts in some regions, rates of
                      intense tropical cyclones, and Arctic Sea ice reduction, snow cover and
                      permafrost.</li>
                      <li> Continued global warming will further enhance the global water cycle, making it
                      more variable and altering monsoon rainfall and severity of dry and wet events.</li>
                      <li> As carbon dioxide emissions increase, oceans and land become less efficient at
                      absorbing and slowing the accumulation of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere.</li>
                      <li> With global warming continuing, every region will experience more and more
                      changes in the drivers of climate impacts. Conductors will be more common at 2
                      degrees Celsius than at 1.5 degrees Celsius, and even more so at higher levels
                      of warming.</li>
                      <li> The collapse of the ice sheets, sudden changes in ocean circulation, and warming
                      beyond currently anticipated are outcomes that are less likely but cannot be ruled
                      out.</li>
                      <li> Limiting anthropogenic global warming requires limiting cumulative carbon
                      dioxide emissions to at least zero. There is also a need to deeply reduce
                      emissions of other greenhouse gases such as methane.</li>
                      <li> Achieving low or very low greenhouse gas emissions will have a significant
                      impact on greenhouse gas and aerosol concentrations as well as air quality
                      within a few years. Notable differences in global surface temperatures will appear
                      in about 20 years.</li>
                    </p>
                    <p>Eaque consequuntur consequuntur libero expedita in voluptas. Nostrum ipsam necessitatibus aliquam fugiat debitis quis velit. Eum ex maxime error in consequatur corporis atque. Eligendi asperiores sed qui veritatis aperiam quia a laborum inventore</p>
                  </div>
                  
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="tab-pane" id="tab-5" role="tabpanel">
                <div class="row">
                  <div class="col-lg-8 details order-2 order-lg-1">
                    <h3>What happen in COP27?</h3>
                    <p class="fst-italic"> The UN Climate Change Conference (COP27) took place from 6 - 20 November
                      2022 in Sharm El-Sheik, Egypt and ended with a breakthrough agreement on a
                      new loss and damage fund for vulnerable countries. </p>
                    <p class="fst-italic">Here is a 10-minute summary of some of the conference's highlights.
                      The UNFCCC secretariat (UN Climate Change) is the United Nations entity tasked
                      with supporting the global response to the threat of climate change. UNFCCC
                      stands for United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change. The
                      Convention has near universal membership (197 Parties) and is the parent treaty of
                      the 2015 Paris Agreement. The main aim of the Paris Agreement is to keep the
                      global average temperature rise this century as close as possible to 1.5 degrees
                      Celsius above pre-industrial levels. The UNFCCC is also the parent treaty of the
                      1997 Kyoto Protocol. The ultimate objective of all three agreements under the
                      UNFCCC is to stabilize greenhouse gas concentrations in the atmosphere at a level
                      that will prevent dangerous human interference with the climate system, in a time
                      frame which allows ecosystems to adapt naturally and enables sustainable
                      development.
                      </p>
                      
                  </div>
                  <div class="col-lg-4 text-center order-1 order-lg-2">
                    <div class="parent">
                   <img class="image1"src="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/GiangSandbox/climatechange/main/img/COP26_Logo.svg.png?raw=true" alt="" class="img-fluid">
                   </div>
                </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </section><!-- End Climate Change Section -->


    <!-- ======= Vietnam's Response Section ======= -->
    <section id="vn-response" class="vn-response">
      <div class="container aos-init" data-aos="fade-up">
        <div class="section-title">
          <h2>Vietnam's Response</h2>
          <p>Positive Responses From The Government</p>
        </div>
          <div class="row">
            <div class="col-lg-12 pt-4 pt-lg-0 order-2 order-lg-1 content">
              <p class="fst-italic">
              <span>Vietnam </span>is one of the fast-growing economies in Asia, which is going through a far-reaching transformation from an inward-looking plan to one that is globalised and market based. Over the last 25 years, with the policy of “đổi mới” (renovation or new changes), Vietnam has transitioned from an extremely poor country to a lower-middle-income country in less than two decades. Vietnam’s goal is to build solid foundations as an industrialised country by 2020. However, after policies in rural development and poverty reduction, there is still a barrier for Vietnam in the path to become a strongly developing country, which is – Climate change. <br/>
              </p>
              <p>
              The sixth-most severely impacted nation by climate change is Viet Nam, where erratic weather patterns have killed people, destroyed infrastructure, and impacted vulnerable communities. The threat to children's access to food, water, education, and healthcare has a significant impact. Urbanisation makes people more exposed, and women are affected disproportionately. By 2050, the Mekong Delta and lowland areas will be affected by droughts, more precipitation, and rising sea levels as a result of global warming. As a result, there will be a decrease in labour productivity, crop yields, natural resource degradation, and loss of assets.<br/>
              By strengthening partnerships, enlisting financial support, stabilising the macroeconomic environment, assisting the post-COVID-19 recovery, and making investments in human capital, innovation, and digitization, Vietnam hopes to maintain the current pace and quicken the implementation of the 2030 Agenda. It is essential to step up initiatives to stabilise the macroeconomy and move toward a green and circular economy. In order to achieve the SDGs for vulnerable groups, especially the poor and racial minorities, inclusive growth and improved transparency and accountability are crucial.<br/>
              </p>
              <p>
              As for now, Vietnam is facing two important difficulties. Firstly, Vietnam needs $400 billion from now to 2040 to effectively respond to climate change, according to the Climate Change Department. The State budget can only cover $130 billion, making it a significant financial challenge. Secondly, interstate management, poor water quality, scarcity, and natural disasters are a few of the difficulties Viet Nam faces with regard to water security. Luckily, the government had made a move to fix the issue. To address these issues, UNESCO, IMHEN, and IHP organised a national workshop. More than 40 participants presented case studies on IWRM, water-sharing agreements, climate change, and water resource management in the Ba River basin while discussing the need for water management, particularly in riverine deltas. Interdisciplinary recommendations for Vietnam's effective water security were provided by the workshop.
            </p>
            </div>
            
              <div class="col-lg-12 pt-4 pt-lg-0 order-2 order-lg-1 content">
                <div style="text-align: end;font-weight:italic;">- Hoang Pham Bao Tran _Sandbox JTC</div>
              </div>
          </div>
  
        
      </div>
<!-- Start Link - Response-->

