    <!-- ======= Vietnam's Action Section ======= -->
    <section id="vn-action" class="vn-action">
      <div class="container aos-init" data-aos="fade-up">
        <div class="section-title">
          <h2>Vietnam's Actions</h2>
          <p>Positive Actions From The Government</p>
        </div>
          <div class="row">
            <div class="col-lg-12 pt-4 pt-lg-0 order-2 order-lg-1 content">
              <p class="fst-italic">
                Vietnam is one of the fast-growing economies in Asia, which is going through a far-reaching transformation from an inward-looking planned to one that is globalised and market based. Over the last 25 years, with the policy of “đổi mới” (renovation or new changes), Vietnam has transitioned from an extremely poor country to a lower-middle-income country in less than two decades. Vietnam’s goal is to build solid foundations as an industrialized country by 2020. However, after policies in rural development and poverty reduction, there are still a barrier for Vietnam in the path to become a strongly developing country, which is – Climate change.            
              </p>
              <p>
                At the COP26 climate conference, Vietnam joined the pledge to reduce global methane emissions in 2030 compared to 2010, and made a 
                commitment to reach net zero emissions by the middle of the century. The international community has highly appreciated Vietnam's strong promises and responsible efforts, which have created new prospects for collaboration on low-emission growth, the promotion of the circular economy, and climate change adaptation. 
              </p>
              <p>
                Phạm Văn Tân - Deputy Director of the Department for Climate Change, said in order to fulfill Vietnam’s commitments at COP26, the Government will soon introduce regulations on reducing greenhouse gas emissions and protecting the ozone layer, the national system to track and evaluate efforts to adapt to climate change, a list of the industries and greenhouse gas emitting facilities that must track their emissions, and a strategy for developing Vietnam's carbon market.
              </p>
              <p>
                By 2050 Vietnam expects:
                <ul>
                    <li>Energy sector emissions will be reduced by 91.6%, and capped at 101 million mtCO2e</li>
                    <li>Agriculture sector emissions will be cut by 63.1%, and capped at 56 million mtCO2e</li>
                    <li>Foresty sector and land use emissions cut by 90%, increase carbon sequestration by 30%, with total emissions and removals reaching at least negative 185 million mtCO2e</li>
                    <li>Waste sector emissions cut by 90.7%, and capped at 8 million mtCO2e</li>
                    <li>Industrial process emissions cut by 84.8%, and capped at 20 million mtCO2e</li>
                </ul>  
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="col-lg-12 pt-4 pt-lg-0 order-2 order-lg-1 content">
              <p>
                <div style="float:left;">
                Furthermore, based on The Prime Minister suggests the concentration on implementing eight contents:
                <ul>
                <li>The conversion to green and clean energy.</li>
                <li>Methane emission reduction plan.</li> 
                <li>Methane emission reduction plan and greenhouse gas emissions plan.</li> 
                <li>The reduction of vehicles using fossil fuels and encouragement of vehicles using electricity.</li>  
                <li>Expanding forests to absorb CO2.</li> 
                <li>Producing construction materials and developing green cities.</li>  
                <li>Accelerating digital transformation.</li> 
                <li>Promoting communication to attract the participation of all people and businesses</li>
                </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="image-holder-right">
                  <img src="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/GiangSandbox/climatechange/main/img/prime.minister.jpg?raw=true" 
                    width="450px" class="img-fluid">
                  <div class="image-holder-right image-caption">
                    <figcaption>Prime Minister Pham Minh Chinh at COP26</figcaption>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </p>
              </div>
              <div class="col-lg-12 pt-4 pt-lg-0 order-2 order-lg-1 content">
                <span>
                <p>
                  Each Vietnam’s industry made some specific changes. As for The Ministry of Foreign Affairs and The Ministry of Planning and Investment will will enhance the mobilisation, The Ministry of Agriculture and Rural Development will review the efforts to the reduction of greenhouse gas emissions in agriculture and forestry. The Ministry of Industry and Trade assumes the prime responsibility for reviewing and finalising the National Electricity Development Plan for the 2021-2030 period, with a vision to 2045. The Ministry of Transport will study and develope a roadmap to convert vehicles using clean energy with the cooperation of The Ministry of Construction. Lasly, The Ministry of Science and Technology shall coordinate with the Ministry of Industry and Trade and other ministries 
                  and agencies, Study nuclear power development, research new energy sources, formulate climate change standards, and promote technology transfer for adaptation.
                </p>
                </span>  
              </div>
              <div class="col-lg-12 pt-4 pt-lg-0 order-2 order-lg-1 content">
                <div class="image-holder-left">
                  <img src="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/GiangSandbox/climatechange/main/img/phamvantan.jpg?raw=true" 
                    width="450px">
                  <div class="image-holder-right image-caption">
                    Pham Van Tan, Deputy Director of the Department for climate change speaking at the workshop. Source: VNA
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div style="text-align:left;">
                    As for now, Vietnam is facing a difficulty. Vietnam needs $400 billion from now to 2040 to effectively respond to climate change, according to the Climate Change Department. The State budget can only cover $130 billion, making it a significant financial challenge. To achieve net zero emissions, Vietnam should prioritize investment in infrastructure, improve forecasting, and engage businesses in green 
                    transformation, low-carbon technology, and energy efficiency projects. Strengthening international cooperation and mobilizing resources from bilateral and multilateral ties is also crucial. In addition, Vietnam is also trying to stop stop rice warming the planet. Rice, Asia’s principal staple, is to blame for around 10 percent of global emissions of methane, a gas that over two decades traps around 80 times as much heat as carbon dioxide. As one of the world’s biggest rice producer, Vietnam’s government is also trying to stop rice production from making worse effect on climate change.                    
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="col-lg-12 pt-4 pt-lg-0 order-2 order-lg-1 content">
                <div style="text-align: end;font-weight:italic;">- Hoang Pham Bao Tran _Sandbox JTC</div>
              </div>
          </div>
  
        
      </div>
    </section><!-- End Vietnam's Action Section -->


