                    <h3>A CALL TO ACTION</h3>
                    <p class="fst-italic">As a student, I believe addressing climate change in Vietnam should consider the country's geography and economy. Below are some solutions I’m thinking of that can be proposed by both the government and citizens, to make a bigger change:
                      <ol type="1">
                        <li>Mangrove Conservation and Rehabilitation Vietnam's coastline is around 3,260 kilometers long, making it vulnerable to sea level rise, storm surges, and other climate-related events. Mangroves are a natural coastal protection system that can help minimize the impact of these events. This method should work for the conservation and rehabilitation of mangrove forests along the coast to strengthen the country's resilience to 
                      climate change.
                      <div class="image-holder-article-right">
                        <img src="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/GiangSandbox/climatechange/main/img/bao-tran/mangrove.jpg?raw=true" 
                          width="300px" class="img-fluid">
                        <div class="image-holder-article-right image-caption">
                          <figcaption>Mangrove forests in Vietnam. Source: VCCI</figcaption>
                        </div>
                      </div>
                      </li>  
                      
                        <li>Promoting Sustainable Tourism Tourism is a significant contributor to Vietnam's economy. However, its growth has led to environmental degradation, particularly in natural and heritage sites. As a student, one can promote sustainable tourism practices that help reduce the industry's environmental impact. This can include educating tourists on responsible behavior, encouraging the use of eco-friendly transport, and promoting local economies that support environmental conservation efforts.</li>
                      
                        <li>
                          
                          Using renewable energy Vietnam's energy production is heavily reliant on fossil fuels, mainly coal. The nation is well-positioned to meet its soaring energy needs through alternative power because it has sufficient and easily accessible renewable sources. By promoting the adoption of renewable 
                          energy sources, such as solar and wind power, we can reduce greenhouse gas emissions in the country.
                          <div class="image-holder-article-left">
                            <img src="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/GiangSandbox/climatechange/main/img/bao-tran/solar-energy.jpg?raw=true" 
