                    <h3>ACT NOW FOR A BETTER VIETNAM</h3>
                    <p class="fst-italic">
                      From the beginning of 2022 until now, climate change has been warned by scientists to reach a serious level, causing extremely bad effects on humanity if we continue to destroy the environment. Ever since then, I have been following the ten actions of ActNow that the UN has given to us. After some time, I have realised that me alone working in changing my lifestyle wouldn't do much, so I believe that you guys should change the ways you live too. Here are some solutions I believe we all should do:
                      <h4>STOP LITTERING THE NATURE</h4>
                        One day, I was kayaking with my mother in Hạ Long Bay. The water was clear and there were small fishes swimming around. It was beautiful, but afterwards, we came across an ocean of garbage which destroyed the view. Ha Long bay itself was recognised by UNESCO as a World Natural Heritage, and now, some parts of Ha Long Bay are polluted by boats and ships.
                      <h5 style="font-weight: bold;">What could happen?</h5>
                        Trashing in wrong areas, especially water surface, contributes to worsening climate change, as they can contain or mix toxic chemicals that make up greenhouse gases. Water in Vietnam is so polluted that it causes almost 80% of the diseases, which contains typhoid, cholera, dysentery and malaria. 
                                            
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      <h5 style="font-weight: bold;">What should we do?</h5>
                        I know that we all enjoy nature, and I’m sure you would want nature to stay beautiful too. If we would stop littering into the ocean, the amount of sea mammals would increase, which benefits the food chain as well as fishermen who live their life selling seafood, and less people will have to get diseases from unclean water. Vietnam’s length of coastline is more than 3000 km from north to south, and if we clear out the coastline litter and trash, the ocean will look more beautiful and paradise-like, attracting people from the world to travel to Vietnam and enjoy its beauty, which also improves the country’s economy. Together, we can become warriors who protect the environment from trash and litter to restore the beauty our world was gifted to.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      <h4>REDUCE FAST FASHION</h4>
                      I love fashion, and I’m sure most people would want to look good too. But little did we know, the process of making clothes also contributes to climate change. 
                      
                      <h5 style="font-weight: bold;">What does it do?</h5>
                      A lot of toxic chemicals are used during the process of making clothes, especially when using cloth dye, because that also contributes to producing greenhouse gases, producing about 10% of annual global carbon emissions, which in the future, might exceed over 50%. And it's all because of using fast fashion. The fashion industry wanted to chase the trends, so they chose fast fashion to produce them quickly at a cheap price, but fast fashion uses fabric material like polyester, which was made out of small strings of plastic, which all the process of making plastic creates greenhouse gases. 
                      <h5 style="font-weight: bold;">What should we wear instead?</h5>  
                      We must reduce the amount of producing and using fast fashion clothes, but then, what are we going to wear now? We can switch to sustainable fashion, use natural cloth dye from flowers, plants or fruit and wear fabrics such as silk, alpaca, and more. That way, we can both benefit the environment, and our health as well (especially silk), since they are naturally absorbent, which makes them breathable and comfortable, this helps our skin stay dry and prevents irritation or allergies. Vietnam stands in 5th place when it comes to silk-making, which also benefits the traditional handcraft villages that are focused on silk-making, lifting them out of poverty and increasing the country’s economy as well as tradition. The world follows trends, and sustainability is becoming one, so why not move to sustainable fashion?
                     </p>
                     <p>
                      <div class="image-holder-article-left">
                        <img src="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/GiangSandbox/climatechange/main/img/tra-my/tra-my-fashion.jpg?raw=true" 
                          width="560px" >
                        <div class="image-holder-article-left image-caption">
                          Advertise traditional silk fabric  - Vietnam Ao Dai
                        </div>
                        
                      </div>
                      </p>
                      <br clear="all"/>
                      <p>
                      <div class="image-holder-article-left">
                        <img src="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/GiangSandbox/climatechange/main/img/tra-my/tra-my-fashion2.jpg?raw=true" 
                          width="560px">
                        <div class="image-caption">
                          Promote Vietnamese traditional embroidery
                        </div>
                      </div>
                      <br clear="all"/>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      <h4>HARMONY WITH NATURE</h4>
                      I want to become an architectural designer when I grow up. I had the idea of designing a smart tech city where people can live with nature which uses renewable energy and electricity transportations to run the city instead of fossil fuels and more.
                      
                      <h5 style="font-weight: bold;">Ecosystem-based adaptation</h5>
                       People have been trying to cope with the climate change issues with stuff that is either very expensive or would just worsen the issue. Take temperature rising for example, people would just stay inside and cool their house down with air conditioning (which uses a lot of fossil fuels), or people would spend money on building barriers to prevent the coastal floodings, even though they could also use another method called ecosystem-based adaptation, where we could plant trees and make a pond to cool the temperature down, and use mangrove forests or coral reefs to weaken the waves that attacks the city. We could use this not just for preventing the world from warming up, but also to help them cool down because plants can absorb Carbon Dioxide.
                      

                       <h5 style="font-weight: bold;">Living green</h5>
                        From my perspective, harmony with nature is living with its features and geography, whether it's a landscape, forest, mountain, coastline, … My city’s structure will be based on nature, geography, natural factors (land, climate) and culture of the area where the city will be built on, so that even though our city is a smart city, it will still illustrate and keep the gifted beauty of Vietnam in that area, and not removing it out of sight to make the city look “futuristic”. Nature benefits us a lot, it gives us calmness, reduces stress, improves our mood, helps us concentrate, solve problems, and keeps us healthy, rather than stressing out from the annoying traffic sounds or having to breath poor air quality.
                        <br clear="all"/>
                      <div class="image-holder-article-left">
                        <img src="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/GiangSandbox/climatechange/main/img/tra-my/tra-my-living-green.jpg?raw=true" 
                          width="560px">
                        <div class=" image-caption">
                         
                        </div>
                      </div>
                      <br clear="all"/>
                      
                      
                        In the end, if you want to change something, you have to act quickly. The problem has already worsened and is challenging Vietnam with alot of climate change issues, but it is not too late for us to act and change our fate, and it is by changing our lifestyles as our way of living also contributes to quickening the process of climate change. If we don’t protect nature, then we can’t protect ourselves, so together, let's put fate into our hands and change it for a better Vietnam.
                      

                    </p>
                    <p style="text-align:right;">- Nguyen Tra My _Sandbox JTC </p>
