              <div class="tab-pane" id="anh-duong" role="tabpanel">
                <div class="row">
                  <div class="col-lg-8 details order-2 order-lg-1">
                    <h3>SMALL CHANGES TO MAKE BIG DIFFERENCES
                    </h3>
                    <p class="fst-italic">
                      <h4>Story of Reflection</h4>                    
                      <h5>The discarded cotton jacket</h5>
                      <span>When my mom was little, my grandma used to make a new woolen sweater for her to wear throughout the holiday season every Lunar New Year.</span><br/>

                      <span>As I grew older, my grandmother stitched a cotton jacket for me instead of knitting it for me. She was overjoyed to have found a great piece of natural cotton fabric to sew this jacket out of. The pastel pink jacket was embellished with lovely cherry blossom motifs and was light yet snug to wear. It completely captivated me.</span><br/>

                      <span>On New Year's Eve, my grandma worked up all night stitching this cotton jacket so that I would have new clothing to wear on the first day of the Lunar New Year. The weather was cold, with a little drizzle, typical of Hanoi's Tet vibe. Even though it was bitterly cold, I felt warm and comfy in my grandmother's cotton jacket.</span><br/>

                      <span>However, Hanoi's Lunar New Year has been increasingly warm in recent years, virtually identical to summer. I can't wear a cotton shirt anymore. It was carefully tucked away towards the base of the cabinet.</span><br/>

                      <span>Even the traditional Tet delicacy, bánh chưng (square sticky rice cake), is more likely to decay due to Hanoi's rising heat…</span><br/>
                      
                    </p>
                    <p>

                      <h4>Small Changes to Make Big Differences</h4>

                      A slew of heartbreaking news has reached us in recent days: landslides causing a series of cars to sink into mud right in Sóc Sơn, Hanoi; soil erosion in Tây Nguyên, where deforestation is rampant; floods in Hanoi; flash floods in the northern mountainous region; and even the heartbreaking story of an elephant in chains...<br/>
                      
                      These stories have left us contemplating and feeling compassion for the land, the trees, the forests, the elephants, and our fellow humans. Humans cannot continue to put themselves at the center and abuse everything around them for their own profit indefinitely. We are merely a speck in the vast and enlightened natural world...<br/>
                      
                      In the face of escalating global climate change, Vietnam has embarked on a journey to combat its environmental challenges, demonstrating that even modest actions can lead to profound impacts.<br/>
                      
                      Vietnam, with its diverse landscapes and rich culture, is particularly vulnerable to the effects of climate change. Rising sea levels, increased temperatures, and unpredictable weather patterns have already begun to threaten the livelihoods of millions. However, the nation has risen to the occasion by implementing a series of small but impactful changes to pave the way for a more sustainable future.<br/>
                      
                      One such change revolves around energy consumption. Traditional sources of energy, such as coal, have long contributed to greenhouse gas emissions. Recognizing the urgency, Vietnam has shifted its focus towards renewable energy sources like wind, solar, and hydroelectric power. Initiatives to install solar panels on rooftops and harness wind energy along the coastlines have gained momentum, gradually reducing the nation's carbon footprint.<br/>
                      
                      <div class="image-holder-article-left">
                        <img src="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/GiangSandbox/climatechange/main/img/anh-duong/anh-duong-transportation.jpg?raw=true" 
                          width="300px">
                        <div class="image-caption">
                          My mother and her coworkers are working on a project to construct urban railway lines in Hanoi.
                        </div>
                      </div>
                      Transportation, another significant contributor to emissions, has also undergone a transformation. The introduction of electric buses in urban centers, urban rail systems, and the promotion of cycling and walking have not only reduced air pollution but also encouraged healthier lifestyles.<br/>
                      
                      <span>In rural areas, changes are equally evident. Agroforestry, which combines agricultural practices with tree planting, helps restore degraded lands while enhancing biodiversity. Farmers are adopting sustainable techniques, including organic farming and efficient irrigation systems, to safeguard their crops and conserve water resources.
                      Education is crucial to this paradigm shift. Schools throughout Vietnam and numerous other organizations are incorporating climate change and environmental conservation into their curricula, ensuring that the next generation will have a profound understanding of the significance of sustainability.
                      </span>

                      
                      

                        Furthermore, community-driven initiatives have emerged, rallying citizens to participate actively in waste reduction and recycling campaigns. Coastal clean-up events have become a regular occurrence, highlighting the significance of marine preservation.

                        These seemingly small changes, when woven together, have created a tapestry of resilience and progress. Vietnam's commitment to addressing climate change showcases how collective efforts can lead to meaningful transformations. As the nation continues on this path, it serves as an inspiring example for others, proving that by making mindful choices today, we can safeguard the planet for generations to come.
                    </p>

                    <span> 

                      "The best time to plant a tree is 20 years ago. The second best time is today."
                    </span>

                    <p style="text-align:right;">- Dao Anh Duong _Sandbox JTC -</p>

                  </div>

                 

                <div class="col-lg-4 text-center order-1 order-lg-2">

                  <div class="image-holder-article-left">
                    <img src="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/GiangSandbox/climatechange/main/img/anh-duong/anh-duong-plastic1.png?raw=true" 
                      width="300px">
                    <div class="image-caption">
                      I participated in a workshop called "Plastic Earth" and learned about the marine ecosystem and the need of environmental protection - 7/7/2018
                    </div>
                  </div>

                  <div class="image-holder-article-left">
                    <img src="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/GiangSandbox/climatechange/main/img/anh-duong/anh-duong-forest1.jpg?raw=true" 
                      width="300px">
                    <div class="image-caption">
                      Cuc Phuong is Vietnam's first national park as well as its first nature conservation unit, which protects, restores, and develops traditional forest habitats while conserving biodiversity - 21/01/2018
                    </div>
                  </div>
                  <div class="image-holder-article-left">
                    <img src="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/GiangSandbox/climatechange/main/img/anh-duong/anh-duong-collect.jpg?raw=true" 
